defaultThe ILO promotes the employability and employment of women and men with disabilities through its standards on discrimination and disability, the development of knowledge on good practice in training and employment, policy advisory and advocacy work, and do
defaultnor-funded technical cooperation projects. 
defaultThe key elements of a rights-based approach 
default–
default equality of opportunity, equal treatment and non-discrimination 
default–
default are contained in ILO Conventions concerning employment in general and persons with disabilities in p
defaultarticular. Chief among the standards used by the ILO to promote the rights and opportunities of disabled persons are the 
defaultDiscrimination (Employment and Occupation) Convention, 1958 (No. 111)
default, the 
defaultEqual Remuneration Convention, 1951 (No. 100)
default, and the 
defaultVocat
defaultional Rehabilitation and Employment (Disabled Persons) Convention, 1983 (No. 159)
default, as well as the 
defaultILO Code of Practice on Managing Disability in the Workplace of 2002
default.
defaultIn November 2012, the ILO Governing Body welcomed the commitment to include people with 
defaultdisabilities in all areas of work of the ILO through a Disability Inclusion Initiative.
